%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FSemiconductor_industry)\n\nPrint/export\n\n* [Download as PDF](/w/index.php?title=Special:DownloadAsPdf&page=Semiconductor_industry&action=show-download-screen \"Download this page as a PDF file\")\n* [Printable version](/w/index.php?title=Semiconductor_industry&printable=yes \"Printable version of this page [p]\")\n\nIn other projects\n\n* [Wikidata item](https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Special:EntityPage/Q2986369 \"Structured data on this page hosted by Wikidata [g]\")\n\nAppearance\n\nmove to sidebar\nhide\n\nFrom Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia\n\nDesign and fabrication of semiconductors\n\n| [Semiconductor device fabrication](/wiki/Semiconductor_device_fabrication \"Semiconductor device fabrication\") |\n| --- |\n|  |\n| [MOSFET scaling](/wiki/MOSFET#Scaling \"MOSFET\") ([process nodes](/wiki/List_of_semiconductor_scale_examples \"List of semiconductor scale examples\")) |\n| * 0[20 μm](/wiki/20_%CE%BCm_process \"20 μm process\") – 1968 * 0[10 μm](/wiki/10_%CE%BCm_process \"10 μm process\") – 1971 * 00[6 μm](/wiki/6_%CE%BCm_process \"6 μm process\") – 1974 * 00[3 μm](/wiki/3_%CE%BCm_process \"3 μm process\") – 1977 * [1.5 μm](/wiki/1.5_%CE%BCm_process \"1.5 μm process\") – 1981 * 00[1 μm](/wiki/1_%CE%BCm_process \"1 μm process\") – 1984 * [800 nm](/wiki/800_nm_process \"800 nm process\") – 1987 * [600 nm](/wiki/600_nm_process \"600 nm process\") – 1990 * [350 nm](/wiki/350_nm_process \"350 nm process\") – 1993 * [250 nm](/wiki/250_nm_process \"250 nm process\") – 1996 * [180 nm](/wiki/180_nm_process \"180 nm process\") – 1999 * [130 nm](/wiki/130_nm_process \"130 nm process\") – 2001 * 0[90 nm](/wiki/90_nm_process \"90 nm process\") – 2003 * 0[65 nm](/wiki/65_nm_process \"65 nm process\") – 2005 * 0[45 nm](/wiki/45_nm_process \"45 nm process\") – 2007 * 0[32 nm](/wiki/32_nm_process \"32 nm process\") – 2009 * 0[28 nm](/wiki/28_nm_process \"28 nm process\") – 2010 * 0[22 nm](/wiki/22_nm_process \"22 nm process\") – 2012 * 0[14 nm](/wiki/14_nm_process \"14 nm process\") – 2014 * 0[10 nm](/wiki/10_nm_process \"10 nm process\") – 2016 * 00[7 nm](/wiki/7_nm_process \"7 nm process\") – 2018 * 00[5 nm](/wiki/5_nm_process \"5 nm process\") – 2020 * 00[3 nm](/wiki/3_nm_process \"3 nm process\") – 2022 * 00[2 nm](/wiki/2_nm_process \"2 nm process\") – 2025 |\n| Future  * 00[1 nm](/wiki/1_nm_process \"1 nm process\") ~ 2027 |\n| ---      * [Half-nodes](/wiki/Die_shrink#Half-shrink \"Die shrink\") * [Density](/wiki/Transistor_count#Transistor_density \"Transistor count\") * [CMOS](/wiki/CMOS \"CMOS\") * [Device](/wiki/Semiconductor_device \"Semiconductor device\") ([multi-gate](/wiki/Multigate_device \"Multigate device\")) * [Moore's law](/wiki/Moore%27s_law \"Moore's law\") * [Transistor count](/wiki/Transistor_count \"Transistor count\") * [Semiconductor](/wiki/Semiconductor \"Semiconductor\") * Industry * [Nanoelectronics](/wiki/Nanoelectronics \"Nanoelectronics\") |\n| * [v](/wiki/Template:Semiconductor_manufacturing_processes \"Template:Semiconductor manufacturing processes\") * [t](/wiki/Template_talk:Semiconductor_manufacturing_processes \"Template talk:Semiconductor manufacturing processes\") * [e](/wiki/Special:EditPage/Template:Semiconductor_manufacturing_processes \"Special:EditPage/Template:Semiconductor manufacturing processes\") |\n\nThe **semiconductor industry** is the aggregate of companies engaged in the [design](/wiki/Electronic_design_automation \"Electronic design automation\") and [fabrication](/wiki/Fabrication_(semiconductor) \"Fabrication (semiconductor)\") of [semiconductors](/wiki/Semiconductor \"Semiconductor\") and [semiconductor devices](/wiki/Semiconductor_devices \"Semiconductor devices\"), such as [transistors](/wiki/Transistors \"Transistors\") and [integrated circuits](/wiki/Integrated_circuit \"Integrated circuit\"). Its roots can be traced to the invention of the transistor by [Shockley](/wiki/William_Shockley \"William Shockley\"), [Brattain](/wiki/Walter_Houser_Brattain \"Walter Houser Brattain\"), and [Bardeen](/wiki/John_Bardeen \"John Bardeen\") at [Bell Labs](/wiki/Bell_Labs \"Bell Labs\") in 1948.[[1]](#cite_note-1)[[2]](#cite_note-2) Bell Labs licensed the technology for $25,000,[[3]](#cite_note-3) and soon many companies, including [Motorola](/wiki/Motorola \"Motorola\") (1952),[[4]](#cite_note-4) [Shockley Semiconductor](/wiki/Shockley_Semiconductor_Laboratory \"Shockley Semiconductor Laboratory\") (1955), [Sylvania](/wiki/Sylvania_Electric_Products \"Sylvania Electric Products\"), Centralab, [Fairchild Semiconductor](/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor \"Fairchild Semiconductor\") and [Texas Instruments](/wiki/Texas_Instruments \"Texas Instruments\") were making transistors. In 1958 [Jack Kilby](/wiki/Jack_Kilby \"Jack Kilby\") of Texas Instruments and [Robert Noyce](/wiki/Robert_Noyce \"Robert Noyce\") of Fairchild independently invented the [Integrated Circuit](/wiki/Integrated_Circuit \"Integrated Circuit\"), a method of producing multiple transistors on a single \"chip\" of Semiconductor material. This kicked off a number of rapid advances in [fabrication technology](/wiki/Semiconductor_device_fabrication \"Semiconductor device fabrication\") leading to the exponential growth in [semiconductor device](/wiki/Semiconductor_devices \"Semiconductor devices\") production, known as [Moore's law](/wiki/Moore%27s_law \"Moore's law\") that has persisted over the past six or so decades. The industry's annual semiconductor sales revenue has since grown to over $481 billion, as of 2018.[[5]](#cite_note-deloitte-5)\n\nIn 2010, the semiconductor industry had the highest intensity of Research & Development in the [EU](/wiki/European_Union \"European Union\") and ranked second after Biotechnology in the EU, [United States](/wiki/United_States \"United States\") and [Japan](/wiki/Japan \"Japan\") combined.[[6]](#cite_note-6)\n\nThe semiconductor industry is in turn the driving force behind the wider [electronics industry](/wiki/Electronics_industry \"Electronics industry\"),[[7]](#cite_note-7) with annual [power electronics](/wiki/Power_electronics \"Power electronics\") sales of £135 [billion](/wiki/Billion \"Billion\") ($216 billion) as of 2011,[[8]](#cite_note-8) annual [consumer electronics](/wiki/Consumer_electronics \"Consumer electronics\") sales expected to reach $2.9 trillion by 2020,[[9]](#cite_note-9) [tech industry](/wiki/Tech_industry \"Tech industry\") sales expected to reach $5 trillion in 2019,[[10]](#cite_note-10) and [e-commerce](/wiki/E-commerce \"E-commerce\") with over $29 trillion in 2017.[[11]](#cite_note-11) In 2019, 32.4% of the semiconductor market segment was for networks and communications devices.[[12]](#cite_note-12)\n\nIn 2021, the sales of semiconductors reached a record $555.9 billion, up 26.2%, with sales in [China](/wiki/China \"China\") reaching $192.5 billion, according to the [Semiconductor Industry Association](/wiki/Semiconductor_Industry_Association \"Semiconductor Industry Association\"). A record 1.15 [trillion](/wiki/Trillion \"Trillion\") semiconductor units were shipped in the calendar year.[[13]](#cite_note-13) The semiconductor industry is projected to reach $726.73 billion by 2027.[[14]](#cite_note-14)\n\nIndustry structure\n------------------\n\n[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Semiconductor_industry&action=edit&section=1 \"Edit section: Industry structure\")]\n\nThe global semiconductor industry is dominated by companies from the [United States](/wiki/United_States \"United States\"), [Taiwan](/wiki/Taiwan \"Taiwan\"), [South Korea](/wiki/South_Korea \"South Korea\"), [Japan](/wiki/Japan \"Japan\") and the [Netherlands](/wiki/Netherlands \"Netherlands\"), with [Israel](/wiki/Israel \"Israel\") and [Germany](/wiki/Germany \"Germany\") having significant presence in the field.[[15]](#cite_note-15)\n\n[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Who_exported_Electronic_integrated_circuits_in_2016.svg/250px-Who_exported_Electronic_integrated_circuits_in_2016.svg.png)](/wiki/File:Who_exported_Electronic_integrated_circuits_in_2016.svg)\n\nElectronic integrated circuit export by country or region as of 2016, by HS4 trade classification\n\n[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Who_exported_Semiconductor_devices_in_2016.svg/250px-Who_exported_Semiconductor_devices_in_2016.svg.png)](/wiki/File:Who_exported_Semiconductor_devices_in_2016.svg)\n\nExport of discrete semiconductors as of 2016, by United Nations Harmonized Commodity Description and Coding Systems 4\n\nUnique features of the industry include continuous growth but in a cyclical pattern with high [volatility](/wiki/Volatility_(finance) \"Volatility (finance)\").[[16]](#cite_note-16) While the current 20-year annual average growth of the semiconductor industry is on the order of 13%, this has been accompanied by equally above-average market volatility, which can lead to significant if not dramatic cyclical swings. This has required the need for high degrees of flexibility and innovation in order to constantly adjust to the rapid pace of change in the market as many products embedding semiconductor devices often have a very short life cycle.[*[citation needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed \"Wikipedia:Citation needed\")*]\n\nAt the same time, the rate of constant price-performance improvement in the semiconductor industry is staggering. As a consequence, changes in the semiconductor market not only occur extremely rapidly but also anticipate changes in industries evolving at a slower pace. The semiconductor industry is widely recognized as a key driver and technology enabler for the whole electronics value chain.[[17]](#cite_note-17)\n\nPrior to the 1980s, the semiconductor industry was vertically integrated. Semiconductor companies both designed and manufactured chips in their own facilities. In many cases, this included inventing new processes, refining and purifying source chemicals and silicon wafers, and even manufacturing equipment, like furnaces, lithography tools and etchers. These companies also carried out the assembly and testing of their chips. Over time, many of these functions were outsourced, such that today semiconductor manufacturers rely on a complex supply chain to provide wafers, high purity source chemicals, and processing equipment. Further, starting with LSI in 1969, the industry has seen the emergence of [Fabless Semiconductor Companies](/wiki/Fabless_manufacturing \"Fabless manufacturing\") that focus solely on chip design and rely on other companies to manufacture their designs. Initially, these other companies were [integrated device manufacturers](/wiki/Integrated_device_manufacturer \"Integrated device manufacturer\") (IDMs), companies that also designed and manufactured their own products, and thus were often competitors of the Fabless companies. But, by the mid-1980's [TSMC](/wiki/TSMC \"TSMC\") and [UMC](/wiki/United_Microelectronics_Corporation \"United Microelectronics Corporation\") emerged as [foundries](/wiki/Foundry_model \"Foundry model\"), specializing solely in the manufacture of other companies' designs.\n\nToday, much of the industry is based on the [foundry model](/wiki/Foundry_model \"Foundry model\"), which consists of [semiconductor fabrication plants](/wiki/Semiconductor_fabrication_plant \"Semiconductor fabrication plant\") (foundries) and integrated circuit design operations, each belonging to separate companies or subsidiaries. Some companies, known as [integrated device manufacturers](/wiki/Integrated_device_manufacturer \"Integrated device manufacturer\"), both design and manufacture semiconductors. The foundry model has resulted in [consolidation](/wiki/Semiconductor_consolidation \"Semiconductor consolidation\") among foundries. As of 2021, only three firms are able to manufacture the most advanced semiconductors: [TSMC](/wiki/TSMC \"TSMC\") of Taiwan, [Samsung](/wiki/Samsung \"Samsung\") of South Korea, and [Intel](/wiki/Intel \"Intel\") of the United States.[[18]](#cite_note-Economist2021-18) Part of this is due to the high capital costs of building foundries. TSMC's latest factory, capable of fabricating [3 nm process](/wiki/3_nm_process \"3 nm process\") semiconductors and completed in 2020, cost $19.5 billion.[[18]](#cite_note-Economist2021-18)\n\nIntel is considering outsourcing some production to TSMC. It currently can only produce 10 nm semiconductors, while TSMC and Samsung can both produce 5 nm.[[18]](#cite_note-Economist2021-18) [GlobalFoundries](/wiki/GlobalFoundries \"GlobalFoundries\"), an American-headquartered firm, uses a 12 nm process for its most advanced chips due to the rapidly increasing development costs of smaller process nodes.[[19]](#cite_note-19)\n\nSemiconductor sales\n-------------------\n\n[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Semiconductor_industry&action=edit&section=2 \"Edit section: Semiconductor sales\")]\n\n### Sales revenue\n\n[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Semiconductor_industry&action=edit&section=3 \"Edit section: Sales revenue\")]\n\n|  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- 